<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-960-552  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 960 552.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 11 1989 v23 n50 p126(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It looks good, but will it work? (assessing training materials)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schneider, Edward W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Evaluating an off-the-shelf training package for a new softwareprogram needs to be done carefully.andP;  Almost certainly, thetraining package will have to be altered to best suit the needs ofthe organization and its workers.andP;  Managers should consult theperson who recommended the program, training developer, trainers,software support specialists, department managers and experiencedusers, always asking specific questions.andP;  For example, theexperienced user should be asked to review how the trainingpackage handles three topics he found elusive.andP;  The manager shouldask himself whether everyone needs to go through the entirecourse.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Training of EmployeesSoftware packagesSoftware Selection.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>